1
00:02:58,561 --> 00:03:01,199
Thank you very much
and welcome to To Tell the Truth.

2
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:05,519
Our first guest, he's made a career out
of being the most outrageous impostor

3
00:03:05,600 --> 00:03:09,599
that we've ever come across
on this show. You'll see what I mean.

4
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:12,079
Number One,
what is your name, please?

5
00:03:12,160 --> 00:03:14,079
My name is Frank William Abagnale.

6
00:03:14,160 --> 00:03:17,439
- Number Two?
- My name is Frank William Abagnale.

7
00:03:17,600 --> 00:03:20,799
- Number Three?
- My name is Frank William Abagnale.

8
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:23,599
From 1964 to 1967,

9
00:03:23,680 --> 00:03:27,599
I successfully impersonated
an airline pilot for Pan Am Airways,

10
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:30,399
and I flew over two million miles
for free.

11
00:03:30,521 --> 00:03:31,600
During that time,

12
00:03:31,680 --> 00:03:35,440
I was also the Chief Resident
Pediatrician at a Georgia hospital

13
00:03:35,520 --> 00:03:38,799
and an Assistant Attorney General
for the State of Louisiana.

14
00:03:38,881 --> 00:03:40,400
By the time I was caught,

15
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:44,719
I was considered the youngest and most
daring con man in U.S. history.

16
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:47,839
I had cashed almost $4 million
in fraudulent checks

17
00:03:47,960 --> 00:03:51,039
in 26 foreign countries and all 50 states.

18
00:03:51,120 --> 00:03:54,240
And I did it all before my 19th birthday.

19
00:03:54,560 --> 00:03:57,439
My name is Frank William Abagnale.

20
00:04:01,760 --> 00:04:04,400
So, for the first time,
he'll have to tell the truth.

21
00:04:04,480 --> 00:04:06,479
We'll start our questioning with Kitty.

22
00:04:06,560 --> 00:04:09,200
Thank you. Number One,
why, with all your talent,

23
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:11,279
and you're obviously
a very bright fellow,

24
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:14,519
why didn't you go in for
a legitimate profession?

25
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:16,720
It was a question of dollars and cents.

26
00:04:16,800 --> 00:04:18,599
When I was a young man,
I needed the money,

27
00:04:18,680 --> 00:04:21,279
and I thought this list of careers was
the easiest way to get it.

28
00:04:21,360 --> 00:04:25,039
I see. Number Two,
I find this all very fascinating.

29
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:27,639
Who was it that finally caught you?

30
00:04:28,480 --> 00:04:30,079
His name was Carl Hanratty.

31
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:34,919
Hanratty.

32
00:04:37,760 --> 00:04:39,760
I am...

33
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:41,719
Carl Hanratty.

34
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:45,239
I represent the F.B.I.
from the United States of America.

35
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:50,799
I have orders to see
the American prisoner, Abagnale.

36
00:05:18,480 --> 00:05:19,919
You sit here.

37
00:05:21,080 --> 00:05:23,079
You do not open the door.

38
00:05:24,120 --> 00:05:25,959
You do not pass him

39
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,159
anything through the hole.

40
00:05:40,720 --> 00:05:41,879
Aw, Jesus.

41
00:06:01,440 --> 00:06:03,440
You know,
I've got a little bit of a cold myself.

42
00:06:04,600 --> 00:06:07,319
Frank, I'm here to read
the articles of extradition

43
00:06:07,401 --> 00:06:10,079
according to the European Court
for Human Rights.

44
00:06:10,161 --> 00:06:11,439
Article One,

45
00:06:11,521 --> 00:06:14,680
extradition shall be granted
in respect of offenses...

46
00:06:14,760 --> 00:06:19,999
Help me.

47
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:23,559
Frank, stop it.

48
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:25,360
Help me.

49
00:06:26,680 --> 00:06:29,839
You don't think
you're actually going to fool me, do you?

50
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:34,560
Sixteen pages to go.
Stay with me. Article Two,

51
00:06:34,680 --> 00:06:37,679
if the request for extradition
includes separate offenses...

52
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:41,759
each of which is punishable under
the laws of the requesting party...

53
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:44,175
Frank?

54
00:06:47,960 --> 00:06:49,279
God damn it!

55
00:06:49,400 --> 00:06:52,479
Get me a doctor in here!
I need a doctor!

56
00:06:52,560 --> 00:06:54,479
- Yes.
- Doctor! Now!

57
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:57,040
Don't sweat it.
We'll get you right to a doctor.

58
00:07:01,400 --> 00:07:04,720
If you can hear me, don't worry.
I'll take you home in the morning.

59
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:06,879
Home in the morning, Frank.

60
00:07:10,320 --> 00:07:12,879
- What are you doing?
- Washing off the lice.

61
00:07:12,961 --> 00:07:16,079
This man has to be on a plane
for America. He has to see a doctor.

62
00:07:16,160 --> 00:07:18,160
Yes, the doctor comes in tomorrow.

63
00:07:18,240 --> 00:07:21,439
I've worked too long, too hard,
for you to take this away from me.

64
00:07:21,520 --> 00:07:24,239
If he dies, I'm holding you responsible.

65
00:07:36,480 --> 00:07:37,679
Oh, Frank.

66
00:08:18,480 --> 00:08:19,919
Okay, Carl,

67
00:08:20,280 --> 00:08:21,759
let's go home.

68
00:08:23,120 --> 00:08:24,719
The New Rochelle Rotary Club

69
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:27,599
has a history that goes back to 1919.

70
00:08:28,280 --> 00:08:29,999
In all those years,

71
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:33,359
we've only seen a handful
of deserving gentlemen

72
00:08:33,440 --> 00:08:35,639
inducted as lifetime members.

73
00:08:36,400 --> 00:08:40,399
It's an honor that has seen 57 names

74
00:08:40,601 --> 00:08:42,559
enshrined on the wall of honor.

75
00:08:42,680 --> 00:08:44,759
And tonight, we make it 58.

76
00:08:45,560 --> 00:08:47,199
So please stand

77
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:51,639
as I present my very good friend,
a man who keeps our pencils sharp

78
00:08:52,121 --> 00:08:53,879
and our pens in ink.

79
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:56,479
Frank William Abagnale.

80
00:09:15,040 --> 00:09:17,039
I stand here, humbled

81
00:09:17,761 --> 00:09:20,559
by the presence of
Mayor Robert Wagner

82
00:09:24,440 --> 00:09:27,640
and our club president, Jack Barnes.

83
00:09:32,280 --> 00:09:35,759
Most of all, I'm honored to see
my loving wife, Paula

84
00:09:38,560 --> 00:09:41,279
and my son, Frank Jr.

85
00:09:41,440 --> 00:09:42,720
Come on.

86
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:50,479
Sitting in the front row.

87
00:09:54,880 --> 00:09:58,399
Two little mice fell in a bucket of cream.

88
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:02,839
The first mouse quickly gave up
and drowned.

89
00:10:03,680 --> 00:10:05,439
The second mouse

90
00:10:06,160 --> 00:10:07,280
wouldn't quit.

91
00:10:07,360 --> 00:10:09,559
He struggled so hard

92
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:12,719
that eventually he churned that cream
into butter

93
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:14,479
and crawled out.

94
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:18,559
Gentlemen, as of this moment,
I am that second mouse.

95
00:10:35,600 --> 00:10:37,840
You're a better dancer
than your father.

96
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:39,679
- Hear that, Daddy?
- Like fun.

97
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:41,159
The girls don't know
what they're in for.

98
00:10:42,360 --> 00:10:44,359
Show him the dance you were doing
when we met.

99
00:10:44,441 --> 00:10:46,080
Oh, who can remember?

100
00:10:46,240 --> 00:10:50,480
The people in that little French village
were so happy to see Americans,

101
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:53,039
they decided to put on a show for us.

102
00:10:53,120 --> 00:10:56,719
- So they crammed 200 soldiers...
- We know the story, Daddy.

103
00:10:56,800 --> 00:10:58,799
into that tiny social hall,

104
00:10:58,880 --> 00:11:01,840
and the first person to walk on stage
is your mother

105
00:11:01,920 --> 00:11:03,839
and she starts to dance.

106
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:06,399
You know, it had been months

107
00:11:06,480 --> 00:11:09,999
since we'd seen a woman,
and here's this blond angel.

108
00:11:10,081 --> 00:11:11,759
Blond bombshell.

109
00:11:13,720 --> 00:11:16,479
And the men
are literally holding their breath.

110
00:11:16,600 --> 00:11:19,479
Holding their breath for you. Hear that?

111
00:11:21,120 --> 00:11:22,879
I turned to my buddies and I said...

112
00:11:22,960 --> 00:11:25,440
I will not leave France without her.

113
00:11:25,560 --> 00:11:26,960
And I didn't.

114
00:11:27,040 --> 00:11:28,439
You didn't.

115
00:11:29,120 --> 00:11:30,399
I didn't.

116
00:11:30,880 --> 00:11:33,079
Oh, shit, the rug.

117
00:11:33,600 --> 00:11:35,199
- Oh, Mom.
- I can't believe I...

118
00:11:35,321 --> 00:11:36,239
It's nothing.

119
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:38,480
- Frankie, run and get a towel.
- Yeah.

120
00:11:38,560 --> 00:11:39,799
Come on.

121
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:46,239
Dance with me, Paula.

122
00:11:56,600 --> 00:11:59,479
Whenever I dance for you,
I get in trouble.

123
00:12:12,761 --> 00:12:15,119
Frank. Wake up. Come on, let's go.

124
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:16,799
Get up, come on.

125
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:19,600
- Frank, wake up.
- Dad.

126
00:12:19,840 --> 00:12:22,159
You don't have to go to school today.
It's okay.

127
00:12:22,240 --> 00:12:25,279
- Why? Is it snowing?
- Do you have a black suit?

128
00:12:25,440 --> 00:12:27,359
I overslept again.

129
00:12:27,480 --> 00:12:30,559
We have a very important meeting
in the city. Eat that.

130
00:12:30,640 --> 00:12:31,839
Come on.

131
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,479
Ma'am, open up, please.
It's important.

132
00:12:34,561 --> 00:12:37,040
What? Oh, gosh.

133
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:40,880
- We don't open for half an hour.
- Just open the door. It's important.

134
00:12:40,960 --> 00:12:43,119
I'm sorry, we don't open for half an hour.

135
00:12:43,201 --> 00:12:44,720
What's your name, ma'am?

136
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:47,279
- Darcy.
- Darcy. That's a pretty name.

137
00:12:47,360 --> 00:12:50,559
I'm in a fix. I need a suit for my kid.
This is my son, Frank.

138
00:12:50,680 --> 00:12:52,240
He needs a black suit.

139
00:12:52,320 --> 00:12:56,479
There was a death in the family.
My father, 85 years old, war hero.

140
00:12:56,880 --> 00:12:59,599
There's a funeral this afternoon,
military funeral,

141
00:12:59,680 --> 00:13:02,639
planes flying overhead, 21-gun salute.

142
00:13:02,880 --> 00:13:05,840
Frank needs to borrow a suit
for a couple of hours.

143
00:13:05,920 --> 00:13:08,479
I'm sorry,
we don't loan suits and we're not open.

144
00:13:08,600 --> 00:13:10,799
Darcy, please. Come back.

145
00:13:12,080 --> 00:13:14,519
Darcy, is this yours?

146
00:13:19,840 --> 00:13:22,359
I just found it in the parking lot.

147
00:13:24,640 --> 00:13:27,319
Must have slipped right off your neck.

148
00:13:29,760 --> 00:13:31,519
Don't hit the curb.

149
00:13:36,001 --> 00:13:39,560
Now get out, walk around the back
and hold the door open for me.

150
00:13:50,480 --> 00:13:52,479
- What's next?
- Okay. Stop grinning.

151
00:13:52,601 --> 00:13:55,600
When I get inside,
go back to the front seat and wait.

152
00:13:55,680 --> 00:13:57,839
Even if a cop comes
and writes you a ticket,

153
00:13:57,920 --> 00:13:59,919
don't move the car, understood?

154
00:14:00,001 --> 00:14:01,679
Dad, what's all this for?

155
00:14:01,760 --> 00:14:03,799
You know why the Yankees always win?

156
00:14:04,480 --> 00:14:05,519
Because they have Mickey Mantle?

157
00:14:05,600 --> 00:14:09,359
No, it's because the other teams can't
stop staring at those damn pinstripes.

158
00:14:09,440 --> 00:14:12,799
Watch this. The manager
of Chase Manhattan Bank

159
00:14:13,360 --> 00:14:16,159
is about to open the door for your father.

160
00:14:18,160 --> 00:14:19,679
Mr. Abagnale,

161
00:14:20,320 --> 00:14:22,319
we don't usually loan money to people

162
00:14:22,400 --> 00:14:24,879
who have unresolved business
with the IRS.

163
00:14:24,961 --> 00:14:27,999
That's a misunderstanding.
I hired the wrong guy to do my books.

164
00:14:28,121 --> 00:14:30,239
A mistake anybody could make.

165
00:14:30,321 --> 00:14:32,959
I just need you guys
to help me weather the storm.

166
00:14:33,080 --> 00:14:35,839
You're being investigated
by the government for tax fraud.

167
00:14:35,960 --> 00:14:38,319
My store is
a landmark in New Rochelle.

168
00:14:38,401 --> 00:14:40,479
I have customers all over New York.

169
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:42,599
You're not a customer
at Chase Manhattan.

170
00:14:42,680 --> 00:14:43,760
We don't know you.

171
00:14:43,840 --> 00:14:46,719
I'm sure your bank in New Rochelle
could help you out.

172
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:48,319
My bank went out of business.

173
00:14:48,400 --> 00:14:50,559
Banks like this one
put them out of business.

174
00:14:50,640 --> 00:14:54,799
I know I made a mistake, I admit that.
But these people want blood.

175
00:14:54,880 --> 00:14:58,519
They want my store.
They've threatened to put me in jail.

176
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:02,239
This is America, right?
I'm not a criminal.

177
00:15:02,320 --> 00:15:05,759
I'm a Medal of Honor winner. A member
of the New Rochelle Rotary Club.

178
00:15:05,880 --> 00:15:09,239
All I'm asking is
for you to help me beat these guys.

179
00:15:09,440 --> 00:15:12,799
It's not a question of winning and losing,
it's a question of risk.

180
00:15:13,760 --> 00:15:17,119
You're the largest bank in the world.
Where's the...

181
00:15:18,041 --> 00:15:19,680
Where's the risk?

182
00:15:24,880 --> 00:15:27,039
How could you let him
take our car like that?

183
00:15:27,160 --> 00:15:30,800
He didn't take anything, we took him.
He overpaid by 500.

184
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:34,399
Come on, Frank. Let's return the suit.

185
00:15:43,001 --> 00:15:44,399
This place is good.

186
00:15:44,480 --> 00:15:47,520
It's small, but it's gonna be
a lot less work.

187
00:15:48,160 --> 00:15:50,120
A lot less work for you.

188
00:16:12,201 --> 00:16:13,479
Hey, Dad.

189
00:16:14,320 --> 00:16:15,360
Hi.

190
00:16:19,120 --> 00:16:20,679
Where is your mother?

191
00:16:21,840 --> 00:16:23,279
I don't know.

192
00:16:23,721 --> 00:16:26,880
She said something
about going to look for a job.

193
00:16:27,880 --> 00:16:31,280
What's she going to be,
a shoe salesman at a centipede farm?

194
00:16:36,640 --> 00:16:38,359
What are you doing?

195
00:16:39,520 --> 00:16:41,399
You want some pancakes?

196
00:16:41,480 --> 00:16:44,519
For dinner? On my son's 16th birthday?

197
00:16:44,600 --> 00:16:46,919
We're not going to eat pancakes.

198
00:16:49,960 --> 00:16:52,759
Why are you looking at me like that?
You thought I forgot?

199
00:16:52,840 --> 00:16:55,799
- I didn't think you forgot.
- I opened a checking account.

200
00:16:57,680 --> 00:17:00,719
I put $25 in the account
so you can buy whatever you want.

201
00:17:00,800 --> 00:17:02,879
- Don't tell your mother.
- I won't.

202
00:17:02,961 --> 00:17:04,359
Thanks, Dad.

203
00:17:05,720 --> 00:17:07,839
Didn't that bank turn you down
for a loan?

204
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:10,119
Yes, they all turned me down.

205
00:17:10,761 --> 00:17:12,479
Then why you opening
a banking account with them?

206
00:17:12,561 --> 00:17:15,280
Because one day, you'll want
something from these people.

207
00:17:15,360 --> 00:17:17,039
A house, a car...

208
00:17:17,481 --> 00:17:19,439
They have all the money.

209
00:17:23,200 --> 00:17:25,319
There's 50 checks there, Frank,

210
00:17:25,400 --> 00:17:27,719
which means, from this day on,

211
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:32,160
you're in their little club.

212
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:34,640
I'm in their little club.

213
00:17:35,240 --> 00:17:37,439
You got that, you got it all.

214
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:39,840
It's even got my name there.

215
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:44,159
- To the moon.
- To the moon.

216
00:17:45,160 --> 00:17:46,560
To the moon.

217
00:17:55,240 --> 00:17:57,439
See that? It's just a school.

218
00:17:58,040 --> 00:18:00,159
No different than Westbourne.

219
00:18:00,240 --> 00:18:02,999
Ma, you said you were going to quit.

220
00:18:06,520 --> 00:18:09,679
Frankie, you don't have to wear
the uniform here.

221
00:18:10,760 --> 00:18:13,239
Why don't you take off your jacket?

222
00:18:13,560 --> 00:18:15,080
I'm used to it.

223
00:18:20,360 --> 00:18:21,839
- Excuse me.
- Yes?

224
00:18:21,920 --> 00:18:23,720
Do you know where room 17,
French is?

225
00:18:23,800 --> 00:18:24,879
Yeah...

226
00:18:38,920 --> 00:18:40,559
You selling encyclopedias?

227
00:18:40,640 --> 00:18:43,119
He looks like a substitute teacher.

228
00:18:58,200 --> 00:18:59,879
Quiet down, people!

229
00:19:00,160 --> 00:19:02,120
My name is Mr. Abagnale!

230
00:19:02,560 --> 00:19:05,680
That's Abagnale, not Abagnolee,

231
00:19:05,800 --> 00:19:08,560
not Abagnelee, but Abagnale.

232
00:19:09,640 --> 00:19:13,719
Now, somebody please tell me
where you left off in your textbooks.

233
00:19:14,400 --> 00:19:16,279
Excuse me, people.
If I need to ask again,

234
00:19:16,360 --> 00:19:17,639
I'm gonna write up the entire class.

235
00:19:17,720 --> 00:19:19,319
Take your seats!

236
00:19:23,760 --> 00:19:25,239
Chapter seven.

237
00:19:25,320 --> 00:19:27,959
Would you please open your textbooks
to chapter eight

238
00:19:28,041 --> 00:19:29,879
and we'll get started.

239
00:19:30,680 --> 00:19:32,519
- Excuse me. What's your name?
- Brad.

240
00:19:32,600 --> 00:19:34,080
Why don't you get up here

241
00:19:34,160 --> 00:19:37,759
in front of the class
and read conversation number five?

242
00:19:51,921 --> 00:19:53,519
They sent for me.

243
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:56,359
They said they needed
a sub for Roberta.

244
00:19:56,520 --> 00:19:58,760
I came all the way from Dixon.

245
00:20:00,040 --> 00:20:01,959
I always sub for Roberta.

246
00:20:02,040 --> 00:20:04,159
Excuse me, why aren't you reading?

247
00:20:05,560 --> 00:20:08,839
I'll never come back
to Bellarmine-Jefferson again!

248
00:20:09,080 --> 00:20:10,799
You tell them not to call me.

249
00:20:10,880 --> 00:20:13,160
Do they think it's easy
for a woman my age

250
00:20:13,240 --> 00:20:16,720
and all the money that it costs to travel?
I tell you, they don't give a damn.

251
00:20:16,800 --> 00:20:18,319
Mr. and Mrs. Abagnale,

252
00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:21,079
this is not a question
of your son's attendance.

253
00:20:21,160 --> 00:20:24,039
I regret to inform you
that for the past week,

254
00:20:24,120 --> 00:20:27,560
Frank has been teaching
Mrs. Glasser's French class.

255
00:20:29,361 --> 00:20:30,599
He what?

256
00:20:31,040 --> 00:20:34,679
Your son has been pretending to be
a substitute teacher.

257
00:20:34,920 --> 00:20:38,199
Lecturing the students,
giving out homework...

258
00:20:38,681 --> 00:20:40,759
Mrs. Glasser has been ill,

259
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:43,880
and there was some confusion
with the real sub.

260
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:47,799
Your son held
a teacher-parent conference yesterday

261
00:20:47,880 --> 00:20:50,119
and was planning a class field trip

262
00:20:50,201 --> 00:20:52,800
to a French bread factory in Trenton.

263
00:20:53,800 --> 00:20:56,080
Do you see the problem we have?

264
00:20:57,881 --> 00:21:01,759
I've a note to miss fifth and sixth period
today. Doctor's appointment.

265
00:21:01,840 --> 00:21:04,320
One moment. I'll be right with you.

266
00:21:06,680 --> 00:21:08,999
- You should fold it.
- What?

267
00:21:09,560 --> 00:21:12,400
That note. It's a fake, right?
You should fold it.

268
00:21:12,480 --> 00:21:15,160
It's a note from my mom.
I have a doctor's appointment.

269
00:21:15,240 --> 00:21:17,959
Yeah, but there's no crease
in the paper.

270
00:21:18,041 --> 00:21:19,799
When your mom hands you a note
to miss school,

271
00:21:19,880 --> 00:21:23,639
the first thing you do is fold it
and put it in your pocket.

272
00:21:23,720 --> 00:21:26,120
If it's real, where's the crease?

273
00:21:35,480 --> 00:21:36,719
Frankie.

274
00:21:51,960 --> 00:21:53,359
Ma, I'm home.

275
00:21:56,240 --> 00:21:59,440
Remember that girl Joanna
I was telling you about?

276
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:01,640
I asked her out today.

277
00:22:02,760 --> 00:22:05,639
Think we're going to go
to the junior prom.

278
00:22:06,400 --> 00:22:08,999
Ma, is this my driver's license?

279
00:22:09,080 --> 00:22:11,520
That's all there is, two bedrooms.

280
00:22:11,640 --> 00:22:12,880
Frankie.

281
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:15,039
You remember Dad's friend?

282
00:22:15,440 --> 00:22:17,639
Jack Barnes. From the club.

283
00:22:17,920 --> 00:22:18,839
Hello.

284
00:22:18,921 --> 00:22:21,039
He came by looking for your father.

285
00:22:21,121 --> 00:22:23,559
I was giving him a tour of the apartment.

286
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:26,439
It's very spacious, Paula.

287
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:33,759
Dad is at the store.

288
00:22:34,480 --> 00:22:35,879
So, Frank,

289
00:22:36,720 --> 00:22:40,239
you're getting to look
more like your old man every day.

290
00:22:42,120 --> 00:22:44,399
Thanks for the sandwich, Paula.

291
00:22:45,280 --> 00:22:47,320
- I'll see you later.
- Wait.

292
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:54,079
Is this yours?

293
00:22:56,840 --> 00:22:59,679
Thanks, Frank.
That's the President's pin.

294
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:03,640
I'd be in deep trouble if I lost that.

295
00:23:09,160 --> 00:23:11,079
I'll see you all later.

296
00:23:20,480 --> 00:23:23,679
Are you hungry, Frankie?
I'll make you a sandwich.

297
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:35,279
Jack wanted to talk business
with your father.

298
00:23:36,440 --> 00:23:39,959
He thinks we should get a lawyer
and sue the government.

299
00:23:40,720 --> 00:23:43,759
That it's not legal,
what they're doing to us.

300
00:23:46,480 --> 00:23:48,760
Why aren't you saying anything?

301
00:23:54,760 --> 00:23:57,599
You're not going to tell him, are you?

302
00:23:59,080 --> 00:24:00,119
No.

303
00:24:00,961 --> 00:24:03,599
That's right. There's nothing to tell.

304
00:24:04,801 --> 00:24:09,079
I'm going out for a few hours to visit
some old friends from the tennis club.

305
00:24:09,160 --> 00:24:12,279
When I get home,
we'll all have dinner together.

306
00:24:12,600 --> 00:24:13,799
Right?

307
00:24:14,720 --> 00:24:18,079
But you won't say anything
because it's just silly,

308
00:24:18,200 --> 00:24:19,480
isn't it?

309
00:24:19,960 --> 00:24:21,959
How could we sue anybody?

310
00:24:27,441 --> 00:24:29,760
Do you need some money, Frankie?

311
00:24:30,160 --> 00:24:33,119
A few dollars to buy
some record albums?

312
00:24:33,440 --> 00:24:35,479
Here. Take $5.

313
00:24:37,080 --> 00:24:38,239
Or 10.

314
00:24:43,881 --> 00:24:46,399
You promised you were going to quit.

315
00:25:04,640 --> 00:25:06,079
Ma, I'm home.

316
00:25:20,440 --> 00:25:21,600
Hey, hey!

317
00:25:21,680 --> 00:25:23,399
You stay away from me. You hear me?

318
00:25:23,480 --> 00:25:26,079
I don't know who you are,
but if you come back here...

319
00:25:26,160 --> 00:25:29,039
Frank, calm down, will you?
I'm Dick Keener.

320
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:33,319
I want you to leave your things here,
follow me into the next room.

321
00:25:33,401 --> 00:25:35,839
Okay? They're all waiting for you.

322
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:40,520
You don't have to be scared.
I'm right here, Frank.

323
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:42,320
I'll always be here.

324
00:25:42,400 --> 00:25:46,319
But there are laws. Everything in
this country has to be legal.

325
00:25:46,400 --> 00:25:49,040
So what we need to do
is make some decisions.

326
00:25:49,120 --> 00:25:50,519
That's what Mr. Keener is here for.

327
00:25:50,600 --> 00:25:53,199
Many times these decisions
are left up to the courts.

328
00:25:53,281 --> 00:25:56,199
But that can be very expensive,
people fighting over their children.

329
00:25:56,280 --> 00:25:57,479
Nobody is fighting.

330
00:25:57,560 --> 00:26:00,199
Look at me, Frank. Nobody is fighting.

331
00:26:08,600 --> 00:26:12,359
Do you remember your grandma? Eve?
She arrived this morning.

332
00:26:12,440 --> 00:26:14,199
Hello.

333
00:26:23,080 --> 00:26:26,279
Do you understand
what we're saying to you, Frank?

334
00:26:27,520 --> 00:26:30,639
Your father and I are getting a divorce.

335
00:26:33,840 --> 00:26:36,439
Nothing's going to change.
We're still gonna see each other.

336
00:26:36,520 --> 00:26:39,959
- Stop it, please. Don't interrupt.
- You don't have to read all of this.

337
00:26:40,041 --> 00:26:42,679
Most of it is for your parents,
boring adult business.

338
00:26:42,760 --> 00:26:45,279
But this paragraph right here,
this is important

339
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:48,400
because it states
who you're gonna live with

340
00:26:49,480 --> 00:26:50,880
after the divorce.

341
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:52,759
Whose custody you will be in.

342
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:55,359
And there's a blank space right here.

343
00:26:56,680 --> 00:26:59,879
I want you to go into the kitchen,
sit at the table

344
00:26:59,960 --> 00:27:01,399
and put a name down.

345
00:27:01,480 --> 00:27:02,599
You can take as long as you want,

346
00:27:02,681 --> 00:27:04,159
but when you come back into this room,

347
00:27:04,240 --> 00:27:06,640
I want to see a name on that line.

348
00:27:06,720 --> 00:27:10,399
Frank, just write down
a name and this will all be over.

349
00:27:10,600 --> 00:27:12,079
It's going to be okay.

350
00:27:12,160 --> 00:27:13,759
Dad, what name?

351
00:27:13,840 --> 00:27:15,079
Your mother or your father.

352
00:27:15,161 --> 00:27:17,919
Just put the name there.
It's as simple as that.

353
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:21,079
And don't look so scared. It's not a test.

354
00:27:21,800 --> 00:27:23,800
There's no wrong answer.

355
00:27:37,880 --> 00:27:39,679
One ticket to Grand Central, please.

356
00:27:39,760 --> 00:27:41,719
That will be $3.50, sir.

357
00:27:42,920 --> 00:27:45,359
Is it okay if I write you a check?

358
00:27:50,360 --> 00:27:52,679
Carl, when do I get to call my father?

359
00:27:53,040 --> 00:27:55,600
You can call him when we get
to New York.

360
00:27:55,680 --> 00:27:57,759
We leave for the airport in seven hours.

361
00:27:59,160 --> 00:28:01,240
Until then, just sit there.

362
00:28:01,400 --> 00:28:02,679
Be quiet.

363
00:28:03,720 --> 00:28:07,359
On the other side of the hotel,
they got suites that face the park.

364
00:28:08,680 --> 00:28:11,319
It's the best room the F.B.I. can afford.

365
00:28:14,040 --> 00:28:16,359
It's okay, I've stayed in worse.

366
00:28:17,040 --> 00:28:18,679
Please. You have to listen.

367
00:28:18,760 --> 00:28:21,959
I don't want to hear your story.
Two checks bounced.

368
00:28:22,040 --> 00:28:23,759
You know how much trouble I'm in?

369
00:28:23,840 --> 00:28:26,239
No, but listen. I'm telling you.
The bank, they made the mistake.

370
00:28:26,320 --> 00:28:27,879
I'll write you another check right now!

371
00:28:27,960 --> 00:28:29,919
What? Do I look like
I was born yesterday?

372
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,759
Look, it's midnight.
Where am I going to go?

373
00:28:32,840 --> 00:28:35,079
You're a goddamn kid. Go home.

374
00:29:21,321 --> 00:29:24,719
I hope you understand. My boss
sent me to Brooklyn, then Queens.

375
00:29:24,800 --> 00:29:26,199
Now he wants me in Long Island

376
00:29:26,280 --> 00:29:28,959
to take a few clients out
for a night on the town.

377
00:29:29,040 --> 00:29:32,799
I'm sorry, but we're not allowed
to cash checks from other banks.

378
00:29:32,880 --> 00:29:35,679
- How would we know if they were good?
- What did you say your name was?

379
00:29:35,760 --> 00:29:37,399
- Ashley.
- Ashley.

380
00:29:37,480 --> 00:29:40,599
You know what I found
on the sidewalk out there?

381
00:29:45,321 --> 00:29:47,959
Must have slipped right off your neck.

382
00:29:51,921 --> 00:29:54,839
Is there something
I can help you with, son?

383
00:29:54,921 --> 00:29:57,120
It's my grandmother's birthday
next week

384
00:29:57,200 --> 00:29:59,720
and I want to get her something
extra special.

385
00:29:59,800 --> 00:30:03,479
Please, it's my midterm next week
and my books were stolen.

386
00:30:05,160 --> 00:30:07,719
Please, just $5.
No one would have to know.

387
00:30:07,800 --> 00:30:11,039
I'm sorry,
but we are not allowed to take checks

388
00:30:11,121 --> 00:30:13,160
from people we don't know.

389
00:30:35,200 --> 00:30:36,959
Welcome to New York.

390
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:54,759
Pleasure to have you back, Captain.

391
00:30:54,880 --> 00:30:58,799
What do you think, Angelo?
The tomatoes are ripe this afternoon.

392
00:31:05,800 --> 00:31:06,879
What have we here?

393
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:08,959
- Can I have your autograph?
- You betcha.

394
00:31:09,040 --> 00:31:10,999
- Can I have your autograph, too?
- You gonna be a pilot?

395
00:31:12,961 --> 00:31:14,639
There you go. Work hard in school.

396
00:31:14,720 --> 00:31:15,999
Dear Dad,

397
00:31:16,080 --> 00:31:18,479
I've decided to become an airline pilot.

398
00:31:18,560 --> 00:31:20,319
I've applied to all the big airlines,

399
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:23,359
and I have several promising interviews
lined up.

400
00:31:23,680 --> 00:31:26,400
How is Mom?
Have you called her lately?

401
00:31:26,480 --> 00:31:28,959
Love, your son, Frank.

402
00:31:32,480 --> 00:31:33,639
Hello.

403
00:31:34,400 --> 00:31:36,400
I'm Frank Black
from Murrow High School,

404
00:31:36,480 --> 00:31:39,079
and I have an appointment
with Mr. Morgan.

405
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:41,839
You're the young man who's writing
the article for the school paper.

406
00:31:41,920 --> 00:31:42,879
Yes, ma'am. That's me.

407
00:31:42,960 --> 00:31:45,279
I want to know everything there is
to know about being a pilot.

408
00:31:46,080 --> 00:31:49,440
What airports does Pan Am fly to?
What does a pilot make in a year?

409
00:31:49,520 --> 00:31:51,159
Who tells them where they're gonna
fly to?

410
00:31:51,240 --> 00:31:53,359
- Slow down. Take them one at a time.
- All right.

411
00:31:53,440 --> 00:31:56,079
What does it mean when
one pilot says to another pilot,

412
00:31:56,161 --> 00:31:57,279
What kind of equipment are you on?

413
00:31:57,360 --> 00:32:01,039
They want to know what aircraft
you're flying. DC-8, 707, Constellation...

414
00:32:01,120 --> 00:32:03,999
And what about those I.D. badges
that I've seen pilots wear?

415
00:32:04,080 --> 00:32:06,320
Every pilot must have two things
with him at all times.

416
00:32:06,400 --> 00:32:09,759
One is his airline personnel badge,
looks just like this one from Pan Am.

417
00:32:09,840 --> 00:32:12,319
The other one is their FAA license.

418
00:32:12,560 --> 00:32:14,800
And that looks just like this.

419
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:20,119
Do you think I could make a copy
of this to put into my article?

420
00:32:20,200 --> 00:32:23,199
Frank, you can have that one,
it's three years expired.

421
00:32:23,280 --> 00:32:25,279
Thanks. And what about
your I.D. badge?

422
00:32:25,360 --> 00:32:26,600
Do you have an extra one
I could borrow?

423
00:32:26,720 --> 00:32:28,159
No, I can't help you there.

424
00:32:28,240 --> 00:32:29,679
Those are special-ordered
from Polaroid.

425
00:32:29,761 --> 00:32:32,479
The only way to get one
is to become a real live pilot

426
00:32:32,560 --> 00:32:33,959
for Pan American Airways.

427
00:32:38,760 --> 00:32:40,399
Pan Am, may I help you?

428
00:32:40,480 --> 00:32:42,719
Yeah. Hello, I'm calling about a uniform.

429
00:32:42,801 --> 00:32:44,959
- Hold for Purchasing.
- Thank you.

430
00:32:45,040 --> 00:32:46,199
Purchasing.

431
00:32:46,280 --> 00:32:48,839
I'm a copilot based out of
San Francisco.

432
00:32:48,961 --> 00:32:50,999
I flew a flight into New York last night,

433
00:32:51,080 --> 00:32:54,239
but the problem is I'm headed out
to Paris in three hours.

434
00:32:54,321 --> 00:32:55,919
How can we help you?

435
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:59,359
I sent my uniform to be cleaned
through the hotel

436
00:32:59,560 --> 00:33:01,319
and I guess they must have lost it.

437
00:33:01,441 --> 00:33:03,640
They lost a uniform.
Happens all the time.

438
00:33:03,720 --> 00:33:06,559
Go down to the Well-Built Uniform
Company at 9th and Broadway.

439
00:33:06,640 --> 00:33:07,679
They're our uniform supplier.

440
00:33:07,761 --> 00:33:09,680
I'll tell Mr. Rosen you're coming.

441
00:33:09,760 --> 00:33:11,639
You look too young to be a pilot.

442
00:33:11,721 --> 00:33:13,279
I'm a copilot.

443
00:33:13,600 --> 00:33:15,079
Why so nervous?

444
00:33:15,520 --> 00:33:19,559
How would you feel if you lost
your uniform first week on the job?

445
00:33:19,681 --> 00:33:22,560
Relax.
Pan Am has got lots of uniforms.

446
00:33:23,200 --> 00:33:24,799
It's gonna be $164.

447
00:33:25,640 --> 00:33:27,679
Great. I'll write you a check.

448
00:33:27,760 --> 00:33:29,799
Sorry, no checks, no cash.

449
00:33:29,920 --> 00:33:32,279
You'll have to fill in
your employee I.D. number.

450
00:33:32,360 --> 00:33:36,319
I'll bill Pan Am, and they'll take it out
of your next paycheck.

451
00:33:37,600 --> 00:33:38,719
Even better.

452
00:33:40,801 --> 00:33:41,959
Dear Dad,

453
00:33:42,080 --> 00:33:44,999
you always told me
that an honest man has nothing to fear.

454
00:33:45,120 --> 00:33:47,839
So I'm trying my best not to be afraid.

455
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:50,919
I'm sorry I ran away,
but you don't have to worry.

456
00:33:51,040 --> 00:33:55,200
I'm gonna get it all back now, Daddy.
I promise. I'm gonna get it all back.

457
00:34:01,641 --> 00:34:03,199
Are you a real live pilot?

458
00:34:03,280 --> 00:34:05,439
I sure am, little lady. What's your name?

459
00:34:05,520 --> 00:34:08,080
- Celine.
- Celine, it's a pleasure to meet you.

460
00:34:08,160 --> 00:34:10,479
It's a pleasure to meet you, too.

461
00:34:14,121 --> 00:34:18,319
That's 50, 70, 80, 90,

462
00:34:18,400 --> 00:34:20,079
$100.

463
00:34:20,161 --> 00:34:22,360
You have yourself a great time in Paris.

464
00:34:22,440 --> 00:34:23,839
I always do.

465
00:34:24,400 --> 00:34:25,759
Excuse me.

466
00:34:27,040 --> 00:34:28,959
I'm John Modiger. I manage this branch.

467
00:34:29,040 --> 00:34:31,159
I want to thank you for coming in
and using our institution.

468
00:34:31,240 --> 00:34:33,239
It's a pleasure to meet you, John.
I'll be back again.

469
00:34:33,321 --> 00:34:34,280
Good.

470
00:34:34,480 --> 00:34:36,799
Have you stayed with us before?

471
00:34:37,120 --> 00:34:40,239
No, I've been primarily based
on the West Coast.

472
00:34:40,800 --> 00:34:42,640
Is it all right if I write you a check
for the room?

473
00:34:42,720 --> 00:34:44,679
- No problem, sir.
- Great.

474
00:34:53,680 --> 00:34:56,799
I was also wondering
if I could write you a personal check?

475
00:34:56,880 --> 00:34:59,959
For airline personnel,
we cash personal checks up to $100.

476
00:35:00,040 --> 00:35:01,639
Payroll checks we cash up to 300.

477
00:35:03,200 --> 00:35:05,759
Did you say 300 for a payroll check?

478
00:35:10,480 --> 00:35:11,879
Dear Dad,

479
00:35:12,080 --> 00:35:15,319
I've decided to become a pilot
for Pan American Airways,

480
00:35:15,400 --> 00:35:17,719
the most trusted name in the skies.

481
00:35:17,800 --> 00:35:21,839
They've accepted me into their training
program and told me if I work hard,

482
00:35:21,920 --> 00:35:24,080
I should earn my wings real soon.

483
00:35:24,160 --> 00:35:27,159
Please get in touch with Joanna Carlton
from the 10th grade.

484
00:35:27,240 --> 00:35:30,240
Tell her I'm sorry that I could not
take her to the junior prom.

485
00:35:30,320 --> 00:35:32,519
Love, your son, Frank.

486
00:36:09,520 --> 00:36:11,599
- Hello, how are you?
- Fine, thank you.

487
00:36:11,680 --> 00:36:13,720
I have a payroll check I'd like to cash.

488
00:36:13,800 --> 00:36:15,199
Certainly.

489
00:36:16,840 --> 00:36:18,159
Excuse me.

490
00:36:18,880 --> 00:36:20,799
I'm sure you hear this all the time,

491
00:36:20,880 --> 00:36:24,319
but you have the most beautiful eyes
I have ever seen.

492
00:36:25,040 --> 00:36:27,440
Yeah, I do get that all the time.

493
00:36:28,320 --> 00:36:29,760
How would you like it?

494
00:36:44,721 --> 00:36:48,839
I'm sorry, sir. We won't have any cash
until the banks open in an hour.

495
00:36:48,961 --> 00:36:52,319
But I'm sure they can cash your check
at the airport.

496
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:54,239
The airport?

497
00:36:54,360 --> 00:36:56,519
Who cashes checks at the airport?

498
00:36:56,641 --> 00:36:59,999
The airlines.
They've always taken care of their own.

499
